The helper is behaviorally fine; the main issues are local readability and the opaque boolean mode.

A tighter version, keeping the mapper in the adapter and preserving signature and behavior, is:

```ts
type UserRow = {
  user_id: string;
  display_name: string | null;
  deleted_at: Date | null;
};

type UserRecord = {
  id: string;
  label: string;
  active: boolean;
};

function m(x: UserRow, b: boolean): UserRecord {
  const row = x;
  const useUserIdWhenLabelBlank = b;

  const trimmedDisplayName = row.display_name === null ? "" : row.display_name.trim();
  const label = useUserIdWhenLabelBlank && trimmedDisplayName === ""
    ? row.user_id
    : trimmedDisplayName;

  return {
    id: row.user_id,
    label,
    active: row.deleted_at === null,
  };
}
```

Why this is better:
- `x`, `y`, and `b` are the real readability problem. If the function signature cannot change, local aliases are the least invasive fix.
- `useUserIdWhenLabelBlank` makes the boolean mode legible at the decision point instead of forcing the reader to infer semantics.
- Splitting `trimmedDisplayName` from final `label` removes mutation and makes the fallback rule obvious.
- The existing comment is low value because it restates the code. If a comment is kept at all, it should explain the mode, not the mechanics.

Comment guidance:
- Best option: remove the comment entirely.
- Acceptable option if the boolean is still hard to understand from call sites:

```ts
// When enabled, blank display names fall back to the database user id.
```

I would not introduce any domain terminology, ports, or layers here. This is a private adapter mapper, so the improvement should stay purely local and mechanical.
